Attention El Dorado County high school students who are interested in making a difference in the community: The El Dorado County Youth Commission is now accepting applications for the 2020-21 school year.

To apply, students must be enrolled in grades 9-12, reside in El Dorado County and be at least 13 years old. Applications are available at most high school counseling offices, as well as online at: charter.edcoe.org/resources/edc-youth-commission and edcgov.us/Government/BOS. Completed applications must be submitted via email by 11:59 p.m. on Thursday, Sept. 10.

For more information contact El Dorado County Youth Commission Advisor Amy Pooley at apooley@edcoe.org.

Read the full story here: https://www.mtdemocrat.com/prospecting/applications-open-for-edc-youth-commissioners/

In an awards season that was shortened by the COVID-19 pandemic, three El Dorado County high schools were nominated for a total of 15 Elly Awards.

A total of 421 nominations came through for the 38th Annual Elly Awards in a range of categories like comedy, drama, musical and scripts for lead and supporting actor and actress, director, costume design, lighting design, set design, sound design, make-up design and overall production.

The Elly Awards celebrate excellence and the outstanding achievements of community theaters and artists in the greater Sacramento area and include theaters within a 70-mile radius of Sacramento. The 38th Annual Elly Awards will be held Sept. 13 at 7 p.m. on Twitch TV. For more information visit ellyawards.com or call (916) 443-8229.

Read the full story here: https://www.mtdemocrat.com/prospecting/local-high-schools-nominated-for-38th-elly-awards/

Hopes for an in-person graduation ceremony at Ponderosa High School were dashed a second time as COVID-19 again took the spotlight Friday on what should have been a stage set for graduates.

But smiles on grads‚Äô faces and exuberance in their steps told a different story ‚Äî it‚Äôs not how they ended their journey but that they accomplished a feat graduates before them never had to face.

Parents drove their high school seniors ‚Äî donned in caps, gowns and masks ‚Äî through the Ponderosa roundabout; sons and daughters exited their vehicles, slipping the masks off to do the ‚Äúwalk‚Äù and take pictures on a festooned stage. The event was live-streamed with pre-recorded speeches.

At the home of Oak Ridge defensive coordinator Darren Jonutz and his wife Kim, there is a fine line between having fun and working diligently. That line is the door in the middle of his four-car garage.

On one side of the door are more than 20 classic arcade games like Need for Speed, Deadpool and NFL Blitz. But once you go through the door to the other half of the garage, the fun and games are over and it is time to work.

Every Tuesday night during the past 11 football seasons, the Trojans‚Äô defense has met at the Jonutz home following practice, where the couple supplies players with pizza and Kim, a former Mrs. Fields employee, bakes an assortment of cookies.

‚ÄúI can‚Äôt even explain to you how good the cookies are,‚Äù said Avant Jacobs, who had five interceptions in 2019. ‚ÄúMrs. Jonutz cooks the best cookies in the area hands down.‚Äù

Read the full story here: https://www.mtdemocrat.com/sports/recipe-for-a-ring/

Local Girl Scout Partners with 3Strands Global on Gold Award Project

‚ÄúMake the world a better place,‚Äù this is a line from the Girl Scout law that means so much to Girl Scouts around the world. As a part of this incredible organization, Allyson Jolly, a rising junior at Ponderosa High School, has been a Girl Scout since kindergarten. Always active in community service through scouting, Key Club, Warm Winters, and FFA her Girl Scout Gold Award project is the most impactful opportunity she has had to date. The Girl Scout Gold Award is equivalent to the Boy Scout Eagle Award with prerequisites and culminating in a lasting and self-sustaining act of community service that must total at least 80 hours of work. These projects provide girls with many life skills such as communication, financing and planning.

Read the full story here: https://www.mtdemocrat.com/prospecting/local-girl-scout-partners-with-3strands-global-on-gold-award-project/

ANNAPOLIS, Md. ‚Äì Jonah Harm a graduate of El Dorado High School in Placerville, Calif., was officially inducted into the Naval Academy Class of 2024 on Saturday, July 19 as part of the basic midshipman training during the Plebe Summer.

Approximately 1,200 candidates are selected each year for the Academy‚Äôs ‚Äúplebe‚Äù or freshman class, and each student is required to participate in Plebe Summer. Last year the Naval Academy received over 16,000 applications for the Class of 2023.

During this time, plebes have no access to television, movies, the internet or music and restricted access to cell phones. They are only permitted to make three calls during the six weeks of Plebe Summer.

The pressure and rigor of Plebe Summer is carefully designed to help plebes prepare for their first academic year at the Naval Academy and the four years of challenge, which awaits them.

Read the full story here: https://www.mtdemocrat.com/prospecting/local-edhs-graduate-inducted-into-united-states-naval-academy/

Despite the COVID-19 pandemic closing the El Dorado County Fair this year, local students involved in 4-H and Future Farmers of America were still able to show and auction their livestock over the weekend.

Thursday through Saturday young farmers from all over the county brought their steer, goats, lambs and rabbits to compete for awards and go to auction. In the past livestock was auctioned off to the highest bidder in person but instead was this year sold in an online format for the first time due to the current health crisis.

‚ÄúThis was the highlight of the year for me,‚Äù said 2020 Supreme Grand Champion Market Steer winner Elizabeth Bloxsom. ‚ÄúI would have been devastated if we could not have had the event his year.‚Äù

Bloxsom, 17, was in this year‚Äôs graduating class at Ponderosa High School and plans to attend the University of Nevada in fall to study nursing. Last year Bloxsom secured the Reserve Supreme Champion award.

Read the full story here: https://www.mtdemocrat.com/news/junior-livestock-auction-bests-pandemic/

After throwing for 3,114 yards in his first year as Oak Ridge High School quarterback in 2019, Justin Lamson has committed to continue his football career at Syracuse University.

After training in isolation over the past few months to stay in shape for the 2020 season, Union Mine High School football players returned to the Diamondback gridiron for the first time July 6.

It was a different but familiar experience for a team that has a new coach, new set of captains and unprecedented health/safety protocols to follow.

Diamondbacks‚Äô new head coach Taylor Duncan and the rest of the coaching staff have been preparing for live practices since the coronavirus shutdown occurred. Before each practice players are required to answer a questionnaire about how they feel to see if they have any symptoms of COVID-19. Anyone who isn‚Äôt feeling well is instructed not to come to practice.

‚ÄúKeeping social distancing in place is probably going to be the hardest part because kids just want to interact with each other,‚Äù Duncan said.

The practices have to be no-contact and the Diamondbacks are mainly doing running and strength drills at the moment.

Read the full story here: https://www.mtdemocrat.com/sports/practicing-with-precaution/

In 2022 Cameron Park Rotary Club continued its annual tradition of awarding scholarships to students from Ponderosa High School. Through the club‚Äôs foundation, the Darol Rasmussen Endowment fund awarded four vocational grants to individuals on the western slope. This year, through the efforts of Cameron Park Rotarians, a total of 11 students in three categories were awarded scholarships or grants, for a total of $21,700.

Scholarships are based on student academic achievement, school and community activities, course work consistent with educational goals and financial need. Special consideration will be given to applications that reveal a match between studies, community activities, career goals and values consistent with those promoted by Rotary. The six Academic Scholarships for 2020 of $2,000 each were awarded to the following PHS seniors in April: Dominic Benedetti, Kaira Bernaldez, Bailey Day, Maia Salter, Isabella Stone and Miles Tresser.

Read the full story here: https://www.mtdemocrat.com/prospecting/cameron-park-rotary-awards-funds-to-11-local-seniors/

Instead of getting to see the hogs in person for a few minutes during the El Dorado County Junior Livestock Auction, bidders got to think about which hogs they wanted for 48 hours in an online auction June 19-21.

With options limited, the El Dorado Junior Livestock auction thought quick and set up an auction online with the help of Susan Taylor Show Services that featured more than 130 hogs for sale. Susan Taylor Show Services is an Orland-based livestock auction consultant that offers various sales services.

A 271-pound hog named Clyde commanded $2,200, which was more money than any other hog. Clyde was raised by Jayden Meyer of Union Mine High School‚Äôs Future Farmers of America (FFA).

Taylor Bacchi, also from Union Mine FFA, was awarded Supreme Champion Market Hog/FFA Grand Champion. She will be able to put this award next to her Supreme Champion Market Lamb award from a year ago. The total for her sale was not available by press time.

Read the full story here: https://www.mtdemocrat.com/news/swine-sells-online/

What would your younger self say to you now? Some Oak Ridge High School seniors found out last week.

Rolling Hills Middle School teacher Jodie Roberts gives all of her eighth-graders a chance to write a letter to themselves right before they enter high school. Four years later she mails the letters back to them and for many it comes as a complete surprise.

Oak Ridge High School senior Alex Dean was excited when he received his letter and only vaguely recalled writing it in eighth grade. ‚ÄúIt was very nostalgic to read because it brought me back to what my life was like four years ago,‚Äù he said. ‚ÄúI was also surprised with what my goals were in eighth grade compared to now.‚Äù

Not all was lost in the 2020 track and field season. El Dorado High School athletes kept competition alive with virtual meets ‚Äî a first for the sport.

Cougar track and field continued independent training after its 2020 season ended abruptly. Athletes turned in some incredible results and personal records as part of El Dorado‚Äôs virtual track meets.

Sophomore Hannah Crone will continue on to compete in the first-ever National Scholastic Athletics Foundation and athletic.net sponsored Virtual National Championships.

Athletes could run on any open track throughout the country and were hand-timed using social-distancing guidelines. Video proof and marks were all uploaded and validated on Athletic.net.

Schools from all across the country participated in these meets, including St. Thomas More in Connecticut.

Read the full story here: https://www.mtdemocrat.com/sports/el-dorado-track-continues-virtually/

Morgan Thomason would have liked to pitch to Folsom on what would have been Oak Ridge High School softball‚Äôs final home game of the season May 5. Thomason would have been on the mound, surrounded by her fellow seniors ‚Äî Emily Thompson at first base, Madison Steele in the middle of the infield, Katelin Eccles in the hot corner at third base and Hayden Greene in the outfield.

Instead the five seniors, along with team manager Michael Hawkins, who‚Äôs also an Oak Ridge senior, were celebrated on their senior day by their families and teammates after not playing a game since taking care of Granite Bay handily 17-7 March 10.

While graduating senior student athletes are traditionally led onto the field by their families to be honored before their last regular season game at home, these Lady Trojans on Tuesday were instead escorted across El Dorado Hills by the El Dorado Hills Fire Department.

Read the full story here: https://www.mtdemocrat.com/sports/surprise-team-spirit-alive-despite-season-lost/

On this new website, the team aims to continue to provide updated helpful resources and information on upcoming Wellness Center news and events. Please take a minute to check it out!

Dear El Dorado Union High School District community,

I wanted to personally reach out to let you know that our anticipated start of school is still scheduled for August 10, 2020.

Yesterday, Governor Gavin Newsom made comments about a possible earlier start to the 2020-21 school year without knowledge or consent from the California Department of Education and the State Board of Education or any school districts. Our start to the 2020-2021 school year is unchanged. As you know this situation changes rapidly. We will keep everyone updated about any changes or modifications to the upcoming school year, but at this time we do not anticipate any change in dates.

Dr. Ron Carruth
Superintendent
El Dorado Union High School District

Dear El Dorado Union High School District community,

I wanted to personally reach out to let you know that our anticipated start of school is still scheduled for August 10, 2020.

Yesterday, Governor Gavin Newsom made comments about a possible earlier start to the 2020-21 school year without knowledge or consent from the California Department of Education and the State Board of Education or any school districts. Our start to the 2020-2021 school year is unchanged. As you know this situation changes rapidly. We will keep everyone updated about any changes or modifications to the upcoming school year, but at this time we do not anticipate any change in dates.

Dr. Ron Carruth
Superintendent
El Dorado Union High School District
(530) 622-5081

Emma Austin wins Democratic Party Essay Contest
text:
Congratulations to our very own Student Board Member, Emma Austin!

El Dorado High School senior Emma Austin won the 15th annual Fred Winn Democratic Party Essay Contest sponsored by Democrats of El Dorado County.

In her ‚ÄúI Want a Future‚Äù essay Emma looks to the year 2050 ‚Äî when more than half of the world‚Äôs population could be living in water-stressed areas. Major coastal cities like New York City could be flooded and destroyed and rain forests could be completely gone.

post_text:
Oak Ridge athletes having great start to track and field season!

It‚Äôs only two weeks into the track and field season and some Oak Ridge High athletes seem to be in midseason form.

Take senior pole vaulter Tyler Burns. On March 4 at Oak Ridge‚Äôs Friendship Meet featuring the schools in the El Dorado Union High School District (Ponderosa, Union Mine, El Dorado and Golden Sierra), Burns broke the school record in the pole vault by clearing 16 feet, 5 inches, which according to Oak Ridge coach Rob Fairley was the best jump in the nation up to date. On Saturday at the Sac State Classic, Burns won the pole vault again with a height of 15-6.

Another pole vaulter, Allie Sahaida, cleared 9-6 on a borrowed pole and placed third. A week earlier, Sahaida vaulted 10-10 at the Sac Town Races, which was the best vault in the section at the time.

‚ÄúNeedless to say, we‚Äôve got two very good pole vaulters,‚Äù Fairley said.

Read the full story here: https://goldcountrymedia.com/news/173236/oak-ridge-athletes-having-great-start-to-track-and-field-season/

This month's Hands4Hope youth spotlight is Kaihan Danesh!
Kaihan is a senior at Oak Ridge High School and has been a
Hands4Hope participant for nearly 2 years.

Kaihan is a regular participant and lead for the Homeless Committee, responsible for funding, organizing and implementing these outreaches. He's a master in sandwich making and coordinating the entire outreach, typically giving direction to all of the participants and volunteers on what is needed and always greeting those we serve with his dazzling smile!

We are thankful to have Kaihan as a participant of the Hands4Hope program!

The Autism Society of California has asked us to share information about the Matthew Paul Finnigan Memorial Scholarship for graduates or graduating seniors from high schools in California on the Autism Spectrum.

Two scholarships will be awarded - one for $2,000 and one for $1,000 for the 2020/2021 school year.

The scholarship may be applied to tuition, room and board, books, supplies, and other necessary expenses related to attendance in post-secondary studies.

El Dorado County Poetry Out Loud champion primes for state competition.

Arts and Culture El Dorado manages El Dorado County‚Äôs Poetry Out Loud competitions, the national poetry recitation contest that was conceived in 2006 by the Poetry Foundation and the National Endowment for the Arts. Students in area high schools compete at the schoolwide level to rise to the county championships, which were held at Imagination Theater Feb. 6. The tension was palpable and the excitement absorbing as five local high school students took the stage to compete for the privilege of advancing to the state Poetry Out Loud Finals in Sacramento.

Read the full story here: https://www.mtdemocrat.com/prospecting/el-dorado-county-poetry-out-loud-champion-primes-for-state-competition/
